        // The previous loop only considered k as an intermediate for paths between i and j
        // that were already active. Now we need to consider paths from k to active_j,
        // from active_i to k, and between active_i and active_j using k.
        // The structure of Floyd-Warshall naturally handles this if k is the outermost loop.
        // Since we are adding k, we need to ensure all pairs (i,j) where i,j,k are active
        // are updated. The previous nested loops achieve this.
        // The standard Floyd-Warshall structure is:
        // for k:
        //   for i:
        //     for j:
        //       dist[i][j] = min(dist[i][j], dist[i][k] + dist[k][j])
        // Here, k is the vertex being added. So we iterate over all currently active i and j.
        // The loops above correctly implement this for the current set of active vertices.

        // Calculate the sum of shortest paths for all pairs of currently active vertices
        long long current_sum = 0;
        for (int i = 0; i < n; ++i) {
